WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.280
I actually think one
of the reasons why

00:00:02.280 --> 00:00:04.360
some of these universities
have made changes

00:00:04.360 --> 00:00:06.960
without provocation from
the Trump administration

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:08.907
is because they wanted
to. They wanted to

00:00:08.907 --> 00:00:10.740
and they thought that
this was a good thing,

00:00:10.740 --> 00:00:13.080
and they were tired
of being held hostage

00:00:13.080 --> 00:00:14.220
by their left wing.

00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:24.320
Right now, people are arguing about
whether cancel culture is back

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:27.320
and this time, coming
from the right.

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:29.440
And it certainly looks
like the suspension

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:31.720
of Jimmy Kimmel and
other controversies

00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:34.760
do represent a kind of
conservative revenge

00:00:34.760 --> 00:00:38.280
for the great woke
cancellations of 2020

00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:40.587
and 2021.

00:00:40.587 --> 00:00:41.920
But I really think
that you need

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:44.840
to understand the conservative
cultural strategy right

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:48.840
now, much more in terms of
institutions than celebrity

00:00:48.839 --> 00:00:49.317
individuals.

00:00:49.317 --> 00:00:52.985
"They care more
about identity politics.

00:00:52.985 --> 00:00:54.860
They care more about
diversity, equity,

00:00:54.860 --> 00:00:55.760
and inclusion."

00:00:55.760 --> 00:00:58.420
Long before the Charlie
Kirk assassination,

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:01.240
the Trump White House saw
a once-in-a-generation

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:04.680
opportunity to try and
push America’s cultural

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:08.960
institutions, movie studios
and TV networks meaningfully

00:01:08.960 --> 00:01:09.860
to the right.

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:12.500
"Well, we want the museums
to treat our country fairly.

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:14.520
We want the museums to
talk about the history

00:01:14.520 --> 00:01:17.760
of our country in a fair
manner, not in a woke manner

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:19.320
or in a racist manner."

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:21.800
This week, I want to talk
about the most significant

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:24.240
of these efforts,
more important even

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:26.080
than the late night TV wars.

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:27.960
And that’s the
administration’s attempts

00:01:27.960 --> 00:01:30.380
to change elite academia.

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:35.090
"They want to directly review
who we hire on our faculty."

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:36.340
"I mean, this is about science.

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:37.547
It’s about curing cancer."

00:01:37.547 --> 00:01:39.880
"I don’t think that we should
believe any of these people

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:43.120
are interested in good
faith reforms of how higher

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:44.260
education works."

00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:46.420
My guest this
week, May Mailman,

00:01:46.420 --> 00:01:49.000
is the perfect person to
discuss the Trump White

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.360
House’s higher education
strategy, because she’s been

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:54.840
the person in charge of it.

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:58.370
So May Mailman, welcome
to Interesting Times.

00:01:58.370 --> 00:01:59.770
Thanks for having me.

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:03.210
So I just want to start with
a very, very big picture

00:02:03.210 --> 00:02:05.330
question.

00:02:05.330 --> 00:02:09.490
Tell me: what is wrong with
the American University?

00:02:09.490 --> 00:02:11.910
Yeah, and I don’t think
it’s every university,

00:02:11.910 --> 00:02:16.050
but I would say in general —
you’ve got a lot of different

00:02:16.050 --> 00:02:17.030
problems.

00:02:17.030 --> 00:02:21.450
And the biggest one
that comes for me

00:02:21.450 --> 00:02:27.210
is a culture of victimhood,
a glorification of victimhood

00:02:27.210 --> 00:02:30.410
that is ultimately bad
for Western civilization

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:32.170
and bad for the country.

00:02:32.170 --> 00:02:35.890
And I think you can notice it
in little pieces, like when Justice

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:38.690
Kavanaugh was going through
his confirmation hearings,

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:40.470
the need for
grievance sessions,

00:02:40.470 --> 00:02:44.370
the need for coloring books,
the amount of emotional

00:02:44.370 --> 00:02:47.010
support people needed to
suffer through Trump’s

00:02:47.010 --> 00:02:48.610
electoral victory.

00:02:48.610 --> 00:02:51.890
And I think that there’s this
culture that universities have

00:02:51.890 --> 00:02:53.810
been perpetuating.

00:02:53.810 --> 00:02:56.455
Maybe — I call it
Meghan Markle syndrome as well —

00:02:56.455 --> 00:02:58.850
where the greatest
good, the greatest height

00:02:58.850 --> 00:03:00.310
that you can be is a victim.

00:03:00.310 --> 00:03:01.510
So I think that’s one thing.

00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:04.690
And I think then pieces
of it trickle down

00:03:04.690 --> 00:03:09.450
to racism and admissions,
racism in hiring. You're hiring

00:03:09.450 --> 00:03:12.530
people to do things based
on their identity rather

00:03:12.530 --> 00:03:13.870
than their ability.

00:03:13.870 --> 00:03:16.790
But I think at the
end of the day,

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:20.210
it all boils down to a
glorification of victimhood.

00:03:20.210 --> 00:03:22.850
What do universities
teach their students

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:25.850
that they are victims
of in your view?

00:03:25.850 --> 00:03:28.730
Yeah, and so it’s not
necessarily that they are

00:03:28.730 --> 00:03:31.150
victims, but that they
should be victims.

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:34.710
That it’s good to be a
victim. That in admissions,

00:03:34.710 --> 00:03:36.110
what is it better to be?

00:03:36.110 --> 00:03:38.790
It’s better to be
in a minority class,

00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:41.650
whether that’s a sexual
minority class or that’s

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:43.530
a racial minority class.

00:03:43.530 --> 00:03:47.590
There’s something better
to being underrepresented,

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:51.570
to being somehow downtrodden
that should be treated

00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:54.180
as preferential or better.

00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:59.200
And that type of behavior
is not only illegal

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:01.780
right? Which is can’t
treat people differently

00:04:01.780 --> 00:04:05.860
on the basis of their race,
but it’s harmful for so many

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:08.250
reasons beyond that.

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:11.462
You just want the best people,
no matter what they look like.

00:04:11.462 --> 00:04:12.920
The type of students
that you want,

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:15.160
you obviously want diversity.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:17.880
And I think Justice Thomas,
when he’s talking about this —

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:21.700
he’s in favor of
diversity, not aesthetics —

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:24.740
but the whole idea of treating
people differently based

00:04:24.740 --> 00:04:28.420
on whether they are
oppressed or oppressors...

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:32.200
And if it’s seen
as Meghan Markle—

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:35.220
why does she want to
appear like a victim?

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:36.800
Because then she’s special.

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:39.660
There’s something good about
the queen not liking you

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:41.940
because you can
then be a victim.

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:42.940
And that—

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:45.880
I’m not sure it’s worked out
actually that well for her.

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:47.420
She has a TV show.

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:48.840
She does, she does.

00:04:48.840 --> 00:04:49.840
She does have a TV show.

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:51.080
I don’t have a TV show.

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:51.760
Not yet.

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:56.580
But then, so you just mentioned that it’s

00:04:56.580 --> 00:04:59.800
reasonable for universities
to want diversity, right?

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:03.900
And so, I think an argument
is obvious argument that

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:07.380
a university might make in
thinking about how these

00:05:07.380 --> 00:05:11.980
issues impact admissions
is to say: Well,

00:05:11.980 --> 00:05:15.640
obviously if you’re trying to
have a diverse student body,

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:19.820
you do to some extent want to
look at the actual experiences

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:20.860
people have. Right?

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:23.980
And if someone has been
victimized in some way by some

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:28.160
set of forces in their life —
material, financial, familial,

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:32.780
whatever, racism included,
let’s call it adversity.

00:05:32.780 --> 00:05:39.020
Can you rule out adversity
entirely as a reason to maybe

00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:41.480
give someone a
kind of preference?

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:45.640
So I think experience
is obviously relevant.

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:49.380
Maybe a 3.8
student body president

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:57.510
is a better applicant than 4.0
video game basement dweller.

00:05:57.510 --> 00:05:59.770
So I think it’s perfectly
fine, obviously,

00:05:59.770 --> 00:06:02.310
to take into
account experience,

00:06:02.310 --> 00:06:05.710
and it does create a much
better student body than if it

00:06:05.710 --> 00:06:09.990
was just totally blind
based on your SAT score.

00:06:09.990 --> 00:06:13.167
But I think the question
is, what you’re celebrating.

00:06:13.167 --> 00:06:14.750
Are you celebrating
the fact that this

00:06:14.750 --> 00:06:16.218
is somebody with nothing.

00:06:16.218 --> 00:06:17.510
Or are you
celebrating the fact

00:06:17.510 --> 00:06:21.150
that this is someone who has
shown that with nothing, they

00:06:21.150 --> 00:06:23.270
can be somebody.

00:06:23.270 --> 00:06:26.870
But so at bottom, your
argument is that what

00:06:26.870 --> 00:06:32.390
universities are failing to
do is adequately reward merit,

00:06:32.390 --> 00:06:36.830
whether in their applicant
pool or in who they’re hiring

00:06:36.830 --> 00:06:42.630
to get on the tenure track,
do research and so on.

00:06:42.630 --> 00:06:45.670
And in many ways,
fail to reward merit

00:06:45.670 --> 00:06:49.910
in ways that are illegal and
violate our civil rights laws.

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:53.590
So the failure to
reward merit is,

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:56.250
I think, not only just a
problem with the universities,

00:06:56.250 --> 00:06:59.790
but it is then therefore
relevant for its relationship

00:06:59.790 --> 00:07:01.150
with the federal government.

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:04.030
And you said at
the start that,

00:07:04.030 --> 00:07:07.670
it’s not every American
University that has these

00:07:07.670 --> 00:07:08.550
problems.

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:10.850
Talk a little bit about
your own experience.

00:07:10.850 --> 00:07:14.410
So you went to a
red or reddish.

00:07:14.410 --> 00:07:16.950
Kansas is sometimes
politically complicated

00:07:16.950 --> 00:07:22.150
but a reddish state flagship
University for undergrad.

00:07:22.150 --> 00:07:25.990
And then you went to a school
in Cambridge, Massachusetts

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:29.210
of some note for
law school, right.

00:07:29.210 --> 00:07:31.870
So you had two kind of
distinct experiences

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:36.030
of different forms of
elite education in America.

00:07:36.030 --> 00:07:40.030
I’m curious both whether you
saw the problems that you

00:07:40.030 --> 00:07:44.030
think the Trump administration
is fighting at work in those

00:07:44.030 --> 00:07:44.570
places.

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:45.903
And also, if you
felt like there

00:07:45.903 --> 00:07:50.790
was a big difference
between Kansas and Harvard.

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:53.270
Yeah, I would
say my experience

00:07:53.270 --> 00:07:59.390
at the University of Kansas,
I felt more a diverse student.

00:07:59.390 --> 00:08:03.410
Kansas is not it’s a white.

00:08:03.410 --> 00:08:04.670
It’s a fairly white state.

00:08:04.670 --> 00:08:07.670
I think we can say that I’ve
noticed that on my visits.

00:08:07.670 --> 00:08:12.550
And so I participated on
the multicultural board

00:08:12.550 --> 00:08:14.970
my freshman year,
which is this.

00:08:14.970 --> 00:08:17.870
Anybody can come and talk
about your experiences

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:19.130
and what needs to change.

00:08:19.130 --> 00:08:20.030
And everything.

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:23.350
My sorority that I was a part
of sororities and fraternities

00:08:23.350 --> 00:08:25.570
pair with each other
for all these events,

00:08:25.570 --> 00:08:30.910
and I wanted to pair with a
black fraternity associations

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:34.929
rather than just the
traditional IFC fraternities.

00:08:34.929 --> 00:08:40.160
So I really like, I think,
identified or felt like I was.

00:08:42.710 --> 00:08:47.160
I don’t a diverse person and
I really wanted to think about

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:51.040
those issues and pay attention
to them in ways not like

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:54.200
victimhood necessarily, but
cohesiveness and bringing

00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:55.420
everybody together.

00:08:55.420 --> 00:08:59.620
And then I did teach for
America just to locate us.

00:08:59.620 --> 00:09:01.060
When were you an undergrad.

00:09:01.060 --> 00:09:03.780
So I graduated in 2010.

00:09:03.780 --> 00:09:09.300
O.K before, some of the
larger racial issues.

00:09:09.300 --> 00:09:13.100
So my last year in law school,
which was the Ferguson,

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:15.940
Missouri, and
you had hands up,

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:19.660
don’t shoot riots all the
way around the country.

00:09:19.660 --> 00:09:26.200
And I went to a few of
the Ferguson die ins

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:28.565
just to walk around and
see what people were doing.

00:09:28.565 --> 00:09:29.940
And it was a bunch
of professors,

00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:31.100
and it was a
bunch of students,

00:09:31.100 --> 00:09:32.350
and nobody did anything crazy.

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:36.680
They just went to the middle
of a road and laid down,

00:09:36.680 --> 00:09:40.880
and there was a
community feeling to it.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:42.640
And there was something
about chanting

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:44.180
with all of your friends.

00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:46.560
The same thing.

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:47.380
No justice.

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:48.740
No no peace.

00:09:48.740 --> 00:09:51.120
No racist police.

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:55.560
That felt communal and
maybe you weren’t achieving

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:57.660
anything, but you were
doing it with your friends.

00:09:57.660 --> 00:10:00.340
And as the president of
the Federalist Society,

00:10:00.340 --> 00:10:02.660
I felt a little
bit of pressure,

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:06.680
I think, to have
a position on what

00:10:06.680 --> 00:10:08.640
I thought about all
these things going on

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:10.730
in the country.

00:10:10.730 --> 00:10:12.480
And were you and did
you think of yourself

00:10:12.480 --> 00:10:15.240
as a political conservative or
a Republican through all this

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:17.700
when you were in
college and afterward.

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:21.620
Yeah, I definitely saw
myself as a conservative,

00:10:21.620 --> 00:10:24.240
which I think made
me way more attracted

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:28.300
to the Trump movement than I
did a traditional Republican.

00:10:28.300 --> 00:10:30.260
And I don’t exactly
know why that is.

00:10:30.260 --> 00:10:32.940
I think it’s just growing
up in the middle of nowhere,

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:36.280
you don’t there’s no where
did you where did you grow up

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:40.120
on the Kansas Colorado
border is a small town called

00:10:40.120 --> 00:10:43.070
goodland that is, in fact,
the middle of nowhere.

00:10:43.070 --> 00:10:45.110
It actually is
not no judgment.

00:10:45.110 --> 00:10:45.830
But it is.

00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:47.370
It is actually.

00:10:47.370 --> 00:10:48.390
Yes, definitely.

00:10:48.390 --> 00:10:50.330
Statistically Yes, Yes.

00:10:50.330 --> 00:10:52.190
Yeah, it was definitely
conservative,

00:10:52.190 --> 00:10:54.990
but kind of weighing
in on societal issues,

00:10:54.990 --> 00:11:01.210
especially on some of these
really tough ones was a tough

00:11:01.210 --> 00:11:06.130
spot for me because why
can’t we all just get along

00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:07.550
as a wise man once said.

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:09.450
So Well, I mean, I’m
interested in this

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:14.010
because when we’re going to
get into the actual things

00:11:14.010 --> 00:11:16.890
that the Trump administration
is asking of universities

00:11:16.890 --> 00:11:18.150
in just a second.

00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:22.290
But one thing that’s striking
about the argument about

00:11:22.290 --> 00:11:24.270
universities is
obviously, in a way,

00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:29.690
it’s one that’s been going on
since William F Buckley first

00:11:29.690 --> 00:11:32.830
emerged on the political scene
and wrote God and man at Yale.

00:11:32.830 --> 00:11:38.410
The conservative argument that
campuses are too liberal, too

00:11:38.410 --> 00:11:42.930
ideologically conformist
that they reward

00:11:42.930 --> 00:11:46.410
victimhood over merit, that
they use affirmative action

00:11:46.410 --> 00:11:48.450
in discriminatory ways.

00:11:48.450 --> 00:11:52.350
These are arguments that
are decades and decades old.

00:11:52.350 --> 00:11:55.650
But there’s a clear sense,
both among conservatives

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:58.090
and some liberals, that
something substantially

00:11:58.090 --> 00:12:01.350
changed in the
middle of the 2010s.

00:12:01.350 --> 00:12:04.890
That took all of
these existing things

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:07.610
that conservatives complained
about and just made

00:12:07.610 --> 00:12:09.290
them much worse.

00:12:09.290 --> 00:12:11.310
And it seems like
that’s what you think.

00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:15.770
I’m curious why you think that
happened and how much worse it

00:12:15.770 --> 00:12:18.050
got.

00:12:18.050 --> 00:12:19.720
Yeah the why.

00:12:22.290 --> 00:12:26.070
And maybe everyone was
already this liberal.

00:12:26.070 --> 00:12:30.330
And I think people,
smarter people than me,

00:12:30.330 --> 00:12:34.710
have blamed social
media and the iPhone.

00:12:34.710 --> 00:12:39.940
You found your community
in Facebook groups

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:44.460
over campus groups, and you
were able to retreat and hold

00:12:44.460 --> 00:12:46.160
your positions more closely.

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:47.410
I buy into that.

00:12:50.180 --> 00:12:56.380
But I think there and I think
the shutting down of speech.

00:12:56.380 --> 00:12:59.660
So what we used to call
political correctness

00:12:59.660 --> 00:13:02.900
and now call wokism.

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:04.080
And I felt that.

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:06.620
So this was
Obergefell decision

00:13:06.620 --> 00:13:10.220
was right after my third
year of law school.

00:13:10.220 --> 00:13:13.100
And this was the same sex
marriage, the same sex

00:13:13.100 --> 00:13:15.140
marriage decision.

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:20.420
And most people that
are young and educated

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:27.020
are in favor of gay marriage
in some way, shape, or form.

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:29.700
But you could
always talk about it

00:13:29.700 --> 00:13:33.780
in some way, what about
this and that and talking,

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:36.847
and I felt like the
speech each element where

00:13:36.847 --> 00:13:37.680
all of a sudden now.

00:13:37.680 --> 00:13:39.680
Oh, I’m sorry, you said
traditional marriage.

00:13:39.680 --> 00:13:40.722
What do you mean by that.

00:13:40.722 --> 00:13:42.500
What does that mean.

00:13:42.500 --> 00:13:47.340
And as the speech got more
constrained than the ideas

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:50.048
had to be pushed
aside a little bit.

00:13:50.048 --> 00:13:51.340
And actually,
people at Harvard

00:13:51.340 --> 00:13:53.660
will say currently
that some of that

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:55.620
had to do also with the
rise of social media

00:13:55.620 --> 00:13:58.240
because you could be
shamed a little bit easier.

00:13:58.240 --> 00:14:00.010
So I got in trouble.

00:14:02.740 --> 00:14:08.020
One day at Harvard because
I had an event with Chick

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:09.980
fil A sandwiches.

00:14:09.980 --> 00:14:13.820
And the Chick fil A people
left their hot bag that you

00:14:13.820 --> 00:14:15.600
put all the sandwiches in.

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:19.940
And so I threw it in a room
with all of the student groups

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:20.760
lockers.

00:14:20.760 --> 00:14:23.540
And somehow this bag was
in front of the gay student

00:14:23.540 --> 00:14:25.140
groups locker.

00:14:25.140 --> 00:14:28.900
And so there was a group
chat going around saying that

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:33.460
the Federalist Society is
trying to basically threaten

00:14:33.460 --> 00:14:36.500
the gay student group because
there was this chick fil A bag

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:38.420
saying, no, that
didn’t happen.

00:14:38.420 --> 00:14:41.540
But the same type of discourse
that might have previously

00:14:41.540 --> 00:14:45.420
happened or benefit of the
doubt or conversation now is

00:14:45.420 --> 00:14:48.760
much easier for them to
go to their group and say,

00:14:48.760 --> 00:14:53.660
I’ve been discriminated
against and then actually have

00:14:53.660 --> 00:14:55.560
a conversation, and
that got cleared up.

00:14:55.560 --> 00:14:58.860
But I do think
this shift, which

00:14:58.860 --> 00:15:02.820
involved both a curtailing
of speech and retreat

00:15:02.820 --> 00:15:06.220
to groups online,
does have a lot

00:15:06.220 --> 00:15:08.940
to do with iPhones,
social media and the way

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:10.240
that we communicate.

00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:12.320
And what about
protest culture.

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:16.940
You clearly had, in the mid
2010s, the rise of a general,

00:15:16.940 --> 00:15:21.100
a general new atmosphere of
protest culture on campuses.

00:15:21.100 --> 00:15:26.500
And part of the argument
from the Trump administration

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:30.260
has been that this
led to a culture

00:15:30.260 --> 00:15:32.760
of overt physical intimidation
for Jewish students,

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:34.870
in particular, when
the protests were

00:15:34.870 --> 00:15:37.490
around issues related to
Israel and Gaza and so on.

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:41.950
But just I think generally
that protest became a means

00:15:41.950 --> 00:15:44.870
of intimidating speech.

00:15:44.870 --> 00:15:49.570
So I somewhat attribute the
rise of this protest culture,

00:15:49.570 --> 00:15:53.830
which I will agree did occur
around then to the same

00:15:53.830 --> 00:15:57.670
actually underlying cause
that I just mentioned

00:15:57.670 --> 00:15:59.630
of people retreating online.

00:15:59.630 --> 00:16:04.990
As people get lonelier,
they want to find groups.

00:16:04.990 --> 00:16:08.390
So the George Floyd protest,
when everybody was locked down

00:16:08.390 --> 00:16:11.390
and no one could do anything
and you couldn’t see anything,

00:16:11.390 --> 00:16:13.170
and here’s this community.

00:16:13.170 --> 00:16:14.430
I mean, it was a community.

00:16:14.430 --> 00:16:16.530
It’s your buddies,
it’s your friends.

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:18.730
And I can’t actually
fault that feeling.

00:16:18.730 --> 00:16:22.098
That’s a very human feeling
that you want to be a part of.

00:16:22.098 --> 00:16:24.390
And then, especially if you
lose a friend group and you

00:16:24.390 --> 00:16:28.190
lose some of the things that
you otherwise would have done,

00:16:28.190 --> 00:16:30.970
then Yeah, protests
seem very attractive.

00:16:30.970 --> 00:16:34.230
Tractive so I want to be
concrete because we’re going

00:16:34.230 --> 00:16:37.650
to talk about the
universities as institutions,

00:16:37.650 --> 00:16:41.790
because that is obviously
where law and policy come in.

00:16:41.790 --> 00:16:46.050
What you’re describing is
a cultural shift, right.

00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:48.950
How is it the responsibility
or to what extent

00:16:48.950 --> 00:16:53.230
is it the responsibility of
universities as institutions

00:16:53.230 --> 00:16:56.010
to have some kind of reaction.

00:16:56.010 --> 00:16:59.550
Like, it’s not the
universities fault that all

00:16:59.550 --> 00:17:01.950
their students were
on iPhones, right.

00:17:01.950 --> 00:17:04.510
And it’s not the universities
fault that students started

00:17:04.510 --> 00:17:05.650
protesting and so on.

00:17:05.650 --> 00:17:08.050
What did the institutions
themselves, in your view,

00:17:08.050 --> 00:17:11.230
do wrong in response
to this shift

00:17:11.230 --> 00:17:15.750
towards political conformism,
protest culture and so on.

00:17:15.750 --> 00:17:20.450
So I think the
universities were too late.

00:17:20.450 --> 00:17:22.990
So on just basic
safety issues.

00:17:22.990 --> 00:17:25.770
So let’s just take the post.

00:17:25.770 --> 00:17:27.950
October 7.

00:17:27.950 --> 00:17:32.080
Anti-Semitic asymmetric,
violent episodes breaking out

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:34.320
across college campuses.

00:17:34.320 --> 00:17:40.620
If you’re letting a Tent
cities fester on your campus.

00:17:40.620 --> 00:17:44.840
And then we’ve heard a lot
from Harvard specifically that

00:17:44.840 --> 00:17:48.640
they were concerned about
shutting some of those down

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:51.100
or citing students because you
can’t just say, hey, leave.

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:52.558
The students aren’t
going to leave.

00:17:52.558 --> 00:17:55.120
There has to be lever, I’m
going to suspend you or I’m

00:17:55.120 --> 00:17:57.203
going to write you up, or
there’s going to be some

00:17:57.203 --> 00:17:58.080
consequences here.

00:17:58.080 --> 00:18:00.640
But if you’ve got a bunch
of international students

00:18:00.640 --> 00:18:03.220
and such a thing might
threaten their visa,

00:18:03.220 --> 00:18:05.020
then you’re not
going to do that.

00:18:05.020 --> 00:18:06.740
So I think there was fear.

00:18:06.740 --> 00:18:09.020
Discipline discipline
would threaten discipline.

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:09.780
Yeah Yep.

00:18:09.780 --> 00:18:13.880
So I think there was too much
fear from University officials

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:17.680
that by taking basic safety
measures that somehow that

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:20.840
would reflect badly on
them, and they were scared

00:18:20.840 --> 00:18:23.580
because they didn’t
want to be criticized.

00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:26.793
And I think there has been
some learning on that of like,

00:18:26.793 --> 00:18:28.460
no, we’re going to
protect our students.

00:18:28.460 --> 00:18:31.320
And I think universally
people learn some lessons

00:18:31.320 --> 00:18:35.040
after October 7 and
University presidents were

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:40.280
fired and replaced, including
at Harvard, at Penn, Columbia.

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:44.260
But in general, what should
they be doing about this.

00:18:44.260 --> 00:18:48.560
I think it’s just buying into
the notion that there has

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:54.680
to be some community aspect
that’s continually fostered

00:18:54.680 --> 00:18:57.020
around a culture
of excellence.

00:18:57.020 --> 00:18:59.520
Otherwise, you
will let a culture

00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:04.320
of victimhood and intimidation
and harassment and negativity

00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:05.240
thrive.

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:08.300
And I think recognizing
that there was a problem,

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:10.840
which I don’t think
they still have done,

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:13.460
but that’s an opportunity
that just has not been seized.

00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:17.680
So just for maximum clarity.

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:19.640
So then you have
a problem that

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:23.800
is in part about
a set of ideas

00:19:23.800 --> 00:19:28.570
having to do with the value
of victimhood that undermine

00:19:28.570 --> 00:19:31.310
the academic and professional
mission of the universities.

00:19:31.310 --> 00:19:33.970
You have that, and then
you have concrete failures

00:19:33.970 --> 00:19:36.390
to provide basic
public safety.

00:19:36.390 --> 00:19:37.850
Is that a fair.

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:39.990
That’s a fair distillation.

00:19:39.990 --> 00:19:41.630
Yes O.K, good.

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:46.610
So let’s now let’s talk about
what the Trump administration

00:19:46.610 --> 00:19:48.270
is trying to do about it.

00:19:48.270 --> 00:19:51.470
So why don’t you
describe for me,

00:19:51.470 --> 00:19:53.810
from your perspective as
the point person for this

00:19:53.810 --> 00:19:56.410
strategy, how the Trump
administration has thought

00:19:56.410 --> 00:20:00.490
about its conflicts with
universities and its attempts

00:20:00.490 --> 00:20:03.990
to of attack both
of those problems.

00:20:03.990 --> 00:20:08.970
So I think day one or day 2
is an executive order that

00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:11.770
discusses universities
specifically.

00:20:11.770 --> 00:20:17.610
Title Vi says that for any
federally funded educational

00:20:17.610 --> 00:20:21.850
institution that they can’t
discriminate on the basis

00:20:21.850 --> 00:20:24.370
of race or national origin.

00:20:24.370 --> 00:20:27.330
And so this has been used
both on the anti-Semitism

00:20:27.330 --> 00:20:30.950
front, which is national
origin and race,

00:20:30.950 --> 00:20:35.970
and then also on what I people
broadly describe as die front.

00:20:35.970 --> 00:20:37.887
And so if you’re going
to be federally funded,

00:20:37.887 --> 00:20:40.262
then we’re going to make sure
that you don’t discriminate

00:20:40.262 --> 00:20:41.190
on the basis of race.

00:20:41.190 --> 00:20:44.450
So it started with
investigations

00:20:44.450 --> 00:20:45.470
sending letters.

00:20:45.470 --> 00:20:48.130
And I think some people
just changed their policies

00:20:48.130 --> 00:20:49.290
at the beginning.

00:20:49.290 --> 00:20:50.790
So pause there for a moment.

00:20:50.790 --> 00:20:54.110
So you how did
you first of all,

00:20:54.110 --> 00:20:57.130
how did you pick which
schools you sent letters to.

00:20:57.130 --> 00:20:59.690
So I think the
Department of Education.

00:20:59.690 --> 00:21:04.090
We primarily relied on
to pick what they either

00:21:04.090 --> 00:21:07.370
knew based on complaints
that had been received.

00:21:07.370 --> 00:21:09.350
And you had House
investigations.

00:21:09.350 --> 00:21:12.250
So a lot of this
information was public here

00:21:12.250 --> 00:21:16.210
and there was in
government databases.

00:21:16.210 --> 00:21:21.410
Some of them are just very
out loud the Uc system.

00:21:21.410 --> 00:21:25.770
So I think there
was some flag waving

00:21:25.770 --> 00:21:28.170
by certain universities.

00:21:28.170 --> 00:21:32.650
And then I think where
they would basically say,

00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:36.170
we’re primarily hiring
minorities for these

00:21:36.170 --> 00:21:36.870
positions.

00:21:36.870 --> 00:21:38.890
Exactly that kind of thing.

00:21:38.890 --> 00:21:41.230
Yes just give me an example.

00:21:41.230 --> 00:21:43.330
Let’s just take
Harvard, for example.

00:21:43.330 --> 00:21:47.550
Harvard has since taken
down its statistics,

00:21:47.550 --> 00:21:49.890
but they used to
have a big comparison

00:21:49.890 --> 00:21:55.210
chart of what their new
hires used to look like

00:21:55.210 --> 00:21:57.350
and what their
hires looked like.

00:21:57.350 --> 00:21:59.770
I don’t three years ago,
something like that.

00:21:59.770 --> 00:22:04.090
And it used to be pretty
heavily white male.

00:22:04.090 --> 00:22:05.690
And then now it’s not.

00:22:05.690 --> 00:22:08.590
And then they
deleted that website.

00:22:08.590 --> 00:22:12.970
So you have all of the pieces
where it’s like an overt focus

00:22:12.970 --> 00:22:16.170
on this where we want, we
absolutely want to lower

00:22:16.170 --> 00:22:17.490
our white males.

00:22:17.490 --> 00:22:19.890
And then there’s an
embarrassment piece of it

00:22:19.890 --> 00:22:21.680
where they then
took the thing down.

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:24.000
So that’s what I would
consider flag waving.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:28.900
So the Trump administration
has lots of data and you can’t

00:22:28.900 --> 00:22:30.400
do everything all at once.

00:22:30.400 --> 00:22:32.500
And so there is a
prioritization issue.

00:22:32.500 --> 00:22:36.300
And I think people have picked
up that the Ivy League has

00:22:36.300 --> 00:22:39.540
been prioritized, which
they’re not the only ones.

00:22:39.540 --> 00:22:43.380
But when you’re thinking about
what the consequences are

00:22:43.380 --> 00:22:47.500
if you are violating Title
Vi or just otherwise have bad

00:22:47.500 --> 00:22:50.420
policies, the federal
government doesn’t have

00:22:50.420 --> 00:22:51.940
to give you grants.

00:22:51.940 --> 00:22:55.420
But is there also a sense
in which the Ivy League sets

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:57.640
the tone for elite education.

00:22:57.640 --> 00:23:00.120
And if you effectively make
an example of these schools,

00:23:00.120 --> 00:23:03.640
you would assume that other
schools will fall into line.

00:23:03.640 --> 00:23:04.720
Is that part of it, too.

00:23:04.720 --> 00:23:07.242
So you want leadership
but leadership

00:23:07.242 --> 00:23:08.200
in the right direction.

00:23:08.200 --> 00:23:09.980
So I think that’s actually
something that Harvard would

00:23:09.980 --> 00:23:11.563
agree with if you
were to ask Harvard,

00:23:11.563 --> 00:23:14.180
what makes Harvard Harvard.

00:23:14.180 --> 00:23:15.040
Why is it special.

00:23:15.040 --> 00:23:17.495
Why don’t you just shut
Harvard down, not have it,

00:23:17.495 --> 00:23:19.620
but you can have all the
rest of the Ivies and will

00:23:19.620 --> 00:23:21.022
the world be the same.

00:23:21.022 --> 00:23:23.480
And Harvard would say, no, the
world would not be the same.

00:23:23.480 --> 00:23:24.820
We must have Harvard.

00:23:24.820 --> 00:23:25.440
Why is that.

00:23:25.440 --> 00:23:26.560
Because they’re leaders.

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:30.980
Like they I mean, also, the
federal government doesn’t

00:23:30.980 --> 00:23:33.740
actually have the power to
shut down Harvard University.

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:37.960
But I would just
in theory, defund.

00:23:37.960 --> 00:23:39.160
You can defund Harvard.

00:23:39.160 --> 00:23:41.100
What’s Harvard’s
special thing.

00:23:41.100 --> 00:23:41.820
right.

00:23:41.820 --> 00:23:44.960
And it is that in
theory, a leader.

00:23:44.960 --> 00:23:47.080
And the question is a
leader in what direction.

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:51.700
And so if you get signals from
the heights of the leaders

00:23:51.700 --> 00:23:55.560
in academia that we’re making
these changes, then Yes,

00:23:55.560 --> 00:23:59.220
that’s obviously hugely
influential for the rest

00:23:59.220 --> 00:24:00.240
of the country.

00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:03.420
So what are schools
supposed to do

00:24:03.420 --> 00:24:06.380
to prove to the
Trump administration

00:24:06.380 --> 00:24:09.980
that they are being good
examples for the rest

00:24:09.980 --> 00:24:11.300
of higher education.

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:17.590
So we actually do plan to have
a formal way that universities

00:24:17.590 --> 00:24:20.270
can say we’re doing
the right things.

00:24:20.270 --> 00:24:22.910
So I think the Trump
administration does not

00:24:22.910 --> 00:24:25.350
want to be all whack-a-mole
or all negative,

00:24:25.350 --> 00:24:29.630
but these are the
principles that universities

00:24:29.630 --> 00:24:32.870
and the Trump administration
and frankly, private donors

00:24:32.870 --> 00:24:36.290
can ascribe to say this
makes a great University.

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:39.510
So those have not been public
yet, but they will be public.

00:24:39.510 --> 00:24:41.950
And I think we’re going
to have a lot of great

00:24:41.950 --> 00:24:46.190
universities signing up as
the forerunners and saying we

00:24:46.190 --> 00:24:49.750
affirm these things, but
nothing will be shocking.

00:24:49.750 --> 00:24:53.630
It will be things like
merit based admissions,

00:24:53.630 --> 00:24:55.990
merit based hiring.

00:24:55.990 --> 00:25:00.790
I think we’d also to see
some attention to the cost

00:25:00.790 --> 00:25:01.753
of admissions.

00:25:01.753 --> 00:25:03.670
So things that are going
to just vary directly

00:25:03.670 --> 00:25:05.510
benefit students.

00:25:05.510 --> 00:25:11.830
Some look at what your foreign
student base looks like.

00:25:11.830 --> 00:25:15.670
Are you importing
radicalism and how

00:25:15.670 --> 00:25:17.130
are you assessing that.

00:25:17.130 --> 00:25:21.290
So a commitment to cleaning
that up foreign funding.

00:25:21.290 --> 00:25:24.350
Is that primarily about
the ideology of students

00:25:24.350 --> 00:25:26.973
admitted or is it a
problem with the numbers.

00:25:26.973 --> 00:25:28.390
Like does the Trump
administration

00:25:28.390 --> 00:25:31.550
have a problem with how
many foreign students elite

00:25:31.550 --> 00:25:33.090
universities admit.

00:25:33.090 --> 00:25:35.670
So I think there’s a fairness
issue that the president has

00:25:35.670 --> 00:25:37.530
talked about with the numbers.

00:25:37.530 --> 00:25:39.190
These are
universities that have

00:25:39.190 --> 00:25:41.310
huge amounts of
federal funding

00:25:41.310 --> 00:25:43.610
and are supposed to
serve American students.

00:25:43.610 --> 00:25:46.470
And instead, they’ve taken
on I think Columbia’s numbers

00:25:46.470 --> 00:25:48.310
were close to percent.

00:25:48.310 --> 00:25:52.370
Harvard’s are around 30
percent of foreign students.

00:25:52.370 --> 00:25:55.370
And that’s not to say anything
bad about foreign students.

00:25:55.370 --> 00:25:57.550
It’s about what are the
opportunities remaining

00:25:57.550 --> 00:25:58.690
for American students.

00:25:58.690 --> 00:26:04.510
So Yes, I think there will be
some focus on what’s the right

00:26:04.510 --> 00:26:05.450
sizing there.

00:26:05.450 --> 00:26:09.230
And as a University, are you
relying on foreign students

00:26:09.230 --> 00:26:14.720
for money or is your
number calculated to having

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:16.340
a good student experience.

00:26:16.340 --> 00:26:22.000
And what I think about with
the foreign exchange program

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.400
is that this was supposed to
be a program where students

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:24.900
come.

00:26:24.900 --> 00:26:25.820
It’s an exchange program.

00:26:25.820 --> 00:26:27.720
You come to the United States,
you learn about the United

00:26:27.720 --> 00:26:29.543
States, you learn
about the US culture,

00:26:29.543 --> 00:26:31.960
and then you take everything
that you’ve learned about how

00:26:31.960 --> 00:26:35.080
great our country is, and you
go back to your home country

00:26:35.080 --> 00:26:37.920
and you spread those ideas.

00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:41.000
And instead, if you have
so large of a number,

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:42.380
then you don’t get that.

00:26:42.380 --> 00:26:46.350
You don’t really understand
because the percentages have

00:26:46.350 --> 00:26:48.600
grown so much that you can
actually just end up having

00:26:48.600 --> 00:26:51.920
your own siloed culture.

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:54.740
How qualified is the
federal government,

00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:56.960
whether it be the White
House, the education

00:26:56.960 --> 00:27:01.480
department and any
other unit to assess

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:02.740
some of these things.

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:09.760
So I think you would concede
that it is already tricky

00:27:09.760 --> 00:27:14.560
to some degree, to assess
how fully in compliance

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:17.640
a University is just with the
Supreme Court’s admissions

00:27:17.640 --> 00:27:18.380
decision.

00:27:18.380 --> 00:27:21.260
I mean, just a minute
ago, you said, well,

00:27:21.260 --> 00:27:25.880
we wouldn’t want universities
to just use SAT scores

00:27:25.880 --> 00:27:27.940
to admit kids.

00:27:27.940 --> 00:27:31.440
But it seems like if you
wanted to have a system where

00:27:31.440 --> 00:27:34.080
you could rigorously assess
racial discrimination

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:38.240
in admissions, aren’t there
just endless gray areas where

00:27:38.240 --> 00:27:40.680
it’s just going to be really
hard to say who’s complying

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:41.540
and who’s not.

00:27:41.540 --> 00:27:45.040
So definitely,
and I think nobody

00:27:45.040 --> 00:27:48.700
in the Trump administration
is trying to run a University.

00:27:48.700 --> 00:27:50.760
It is too taxing.

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:53.060
And nobody actually wants
to run a University.

00:27:53.060 --> 00:27:54.140
Nobody ever.

00:27:54.140 --> 00:28:00.360
Yes so I think there’s a
line of how do you ensure

00:28:00.360 --> 00:28:03.280
compliance with civil rights.

00:28:03.280 --> 00:28:06.280
And that your
taxpayer money is

00:28:06.280 --> 00:28:09.440
going to a good place versus
a bad place, which is broader

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:11.600
than a civil rights question.

00:28:11.600 --> 00:28:13.760
So you need some
level of control.

00:28:13.760 --> 00:28:16.980
But at the end of the day,
you want independent entities.

00:28:16.980 --> 00:28:19.360
Like on one hand, there’s
just the Hillsdale model.

00:28:19.360 --> 00:28:21.678
Like if you’re going to
take the money then Yeah,

00:28:21.678 --> 00:28:23.220
there’s going to be
strings attached.

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:24.900
But you don’t have
to take the money.

00:28:24.900 --> 00:28:27.380
And if your research
was Hillsdale College,

00:28:27.380 --> 00:28:30.520
just so listeners is the
conservative liberal arts

00:28:30.520 --> 00:28:33.920
school in Michigan one of a
few schools that doesn’t take

00:28:33.920 --> 00:28:35.200
federal funding.

00:28:35.200 --> 00:28:35.700
right.

00:28:35.700 --> 00:28:38.380
And so that’s
always an option.

00:28:38.380 --> 00:28:42.080
Like if anybody thinks that
any of this is too burdensome,

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:45.660
especially very
well-funded universities,

00:28:45.660 --> 00:28:48.260
then just do none of it.

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:50.440
Just be Hillsdale.

00:28:50.440 --> 00:28:53.180
And it’s funny, because
for research, I mean,

00:28:53.180 --> 00:28:55.840
people don’t really understand
the massive amount of money

00:28:55.840 --> 00:28:57.340
that goes to research.

00:28:57.340 --> 00:28:59.780
There’s billions and billions
like Harvard right now,

00:28:59.780 --> 00:29:04.820
I think has something like $7
billion of promised grants.

00:29:04.820 --> 00:29:08.080
These are huge, huge numbers.

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:11.250
But if all of the
research was good,

00:29:11.250 --> 00:29:14.650
if these were research that
was going to create something

00:29:14.650 --> 00:29:17.530
that was going to cure
cancer, then a donor

00:29:17.530 --> 00:29:19.310
would love to fund that.

00:29:19.310 --> 00:29:23.130
I mean, to be the person
that cured cancer.

00:29:23.130 --> 00:29:24.093
And so.

00:29:24.093 --> 00:29:25.510
Well, wait, wait
a minute, though.

00:29:25.510 --> 00:29:28.250
I mean, everybody
wants to cure cancer.

00:29:28.250 --> 00:29:32.570
But donors have
finite resources.

00:29:32.570 --> 00:29:35.610
One of the assumptions behind
public funding of universities

00:29:35.610 --> 00:29:38.190
is that there are
certain goods,

00:29:38.190 --> 00:29:41.030
including medical
research and research,

00:29:41.030 --> 00:29:44.290
for all kinds of
different diseases,

00:29:44.290 --> 00:29:47.750
that you can’t just rely
on donor funding for.

00:29:47.750 --> 00:29:51.570
And that has been
the theory behind

00:29:51.570 --> 00:29:55.170
public private partnerships
in American life going back

00:29:55.170 --> 00:29:56.530
decades.

00:29:56.530 --> 00:29:57.992
Do you think that’s good.

00:29:57.992 --> 00:29:58.950
Like do you think that.

00:29:58.950 --> 00:30:00.700
Do you think the federal
government should

00:30:00.700 --> 00:30:02.370
be funding cancer research.

00:30:02.370 --> 00:30:06.570
Absolutely O.K. So it’s not
just like donors will pick up

00:30:06.570 --> 00:30:07.070
the Slack.

00:30:07.070 --> 00:30:10.230
There is good research that
we want the government funded.

00:30:10.230 --> 00:30:11.350
There is good research.

00:30:11.350 --> 00:30:14.210
But your same question of
how closely can you actually

00:30:14.210 --> 00:30:19.550
monitor a university’s
ability to just do a good job,

00:30:19.550 --> 00:30:24.820
be merit based, have not be
importing radicalism like

00:30:24.820 --> 00:30:26.070
these are difficult questions.

00:30:26.070 --> 00:30:27.445
How are you going
to assess that.

00:30:27.445 --> 00:30:30.990
It’s the same question,
frankly, for all these grants,

00:30:30.990 --> 00:30:34.810
how are you actually going to
monitor where this is being

00:30:34.810 --> 00:30:38.890
used, what the types
of research are,

00:30:38.890 --> 00:30:41.710
how great the overhead when
you do have the overhead,

00:30:41.710 --> 00:30:44.570
is it going to the sports
stadium or is it going

00:30:44.570 --> 00:30:45.770
to salaries.

00:30:45.770 --> 00:30:48.250
If it’s going to salaries
who’s these gets a bit

00:30:48.250 --> 00:30:49.750
difficult questions.

00:30:49.750 --> 00:30:55.290
And so I think the problem
is not whether the government

00:30:55.290 --> 00:30:57.590
should or shouldn’t be
funding cancer research.

00:30:57.590 --> 00:30:59.190
It absolutely should.

00:30:59.190 --> 00:31:03.650
But the unwieldiness of
it has led to basically

00:31:03.650 --> 00:31:06.160
an unchecked situation.

00:31:06.160 --> 00:31:10.100
And so I think it is actually
proper to have a right sizing

00:31:10.100 --> 00:31:13.500
where universities are relying
on the federal government

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:15.900
to a certain extent, where
these are things that

00:31:15.900 --> 00:31:18.820
are maybe not close
to a breakthrough,

00:31:18.820 --> 00:31:21.700
and that there
is an opportunity

00:31:21.700 --> 00:31:26.340
for the private sector to
spend money in ways that

00:31:26.340 --> 00:31:28.567
are beneficial to society.

00:31:28.567 --> 00:31:30.900
And to the extent people have
problems with billionaires

00:31:30.900 --> 00:31:36.140
buying an extra jet
or an extra yacht,

00:31:36.140 --> 00:31:38.820
what are we doing to
incentivize people to actually

00:31:38.820 --> 00:31:41.260
spend on beneficial causes.

00:31:41.260 --> 00:31:45.980
So in effect here, you’re
saying basically that.

00:31:45.980 --> 00:31:49.420
Harvard is very good
at getting billionaires

00:31:49.420 --> 00:31:52.020
to give it money.

00:31:52.020 --> 00:31:55.260
And you’re saying if some of
Harvard’s research funding is

00:31:55.260 --> 00:31:58.280
threatened, then it’s
not a bad thing at all.

00:31:58.280 --> 00:32:01.980
If Harvard calls up its
billionaire donors and says,

00:32:01.980 --> 00:32:05.220
hey, we don’t like what the
federal government is asking

00:32:05.220 --> 00:32:05.720
of us.

00:32:05.720 --> 00:32:08.000
We want you to fund this
cancer research instead.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:09.620
You’d say, that’s fine.

00:32:09.620 --> 00:32:14.420
Wealthy people funding
universities, funding, science

00:32:14.420 --> 00:32:15.000
funding.

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:17.620
Our future is
something that has

00:32:17.620 --> 00:32:19.400
no history in this country.

00:32:19.400 --> 00:32:21.280
It’s absolutely a good thing.

00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:27.180
But I’m just the reason I’m
asking about the difficulty

00:32:27.180 --> 00:32:30.980
of assessing these things is
not because you have to have

00:32:30.980 --> 00:32:33.500
a perfect system.

00:32:33.500 --> 00:32:37.220
In order to have a federal
relationship to universities.

00:32:37.220 --> 00:32:40.360
It’s more just that you guys
are involved in negotiations,

00:32:40.360 --> 00:32:44.420
specific negotiations with
universities that have

00:32:44.420 --> 00:32:47.740
concrete asks.

00:32:47.740 --> 00:32:50.620
And so I’m just trying
to understand how you get

00:32:50.620 --> 00:32:52.820
to the concrete ask.

00:32:52.820 --> 00:32:55.780
One aspect of this is that
the Trump administration has

00:32:55.780 --> 00:32:58.980
been asking, and in some
cases has successfully

00:32:58.980 --> 00:33:02.900
induced elite schools to
pay pretty big settlements

00:33:02.900 --> 00:33:05.200
fines effectively to
the federal government.

00:33:05.200 --> 00:33:07.120
How does that fit
into the picture.

00:33:07.120 --> 00:33:08.800
Is this just punishment.

00:33:08.800 --> 00:33:10.600
Is it revenue for the
federal government.

00:33:10.600 --> 00:33:12.800
What is the purpose of
those kind of settlements.

00:33:12.800 --> 00:33:15.160
So these are large numbers.

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:17.560
And so not to minimize that.

00:33:17.560 --> 00:33:21.620
But the Brown settlement and
the Columbia settlement each

00:33:21.620 --> 00:33:25.080
represented 1 percent
of the endowment.

00:33:25.080 --> 00:33:27.440
So these are things that
the universities can afford.

00:33:27.440 --> 00:33:29.740
And in a sense, it’s
giving back a very,

00:33:29.740 --> 00:33:34.820
very small percentage of money
that goes to these schools

00:33:34.820 --> 00:33:36.620
every year.

00:33:36.620 --> 00:33:43.040
So I think there’s a
recognition, of course,

00:33:43.040 --> 00:33:45.420
there’s no recognition of
fault. These are settlements.

00:33:45.420 --> 00:33:47.560
But by paying
some of this back,

00:33:47.560 --> 00:33:52.220
I think there is a somewhat
for the public sense

00:33:52.220 --> 00:33:55.040
of acknowledgment of
wrongdoing, not a legal sense,

00:33:55.040 --> 00:33:59.020
but a mortal sense of we’ve
taken all this money and we

00:33:59.020 --> 00:34:02.550
did it in ways that were not
merit based or they weren’t

00:34:02.550 --> 00:34:04.010
safe for our students.

00:34:04.010 --> 00:34:05.970
And so we’re paying a
small amount of it back.

00:34:05.970 --> 00:34:08.710
But then I think also
having that dollar figure,

00:34:08.710 --> 00:34:12.270
It actually brings attention
to the deals in ways people

00:34:12.270 --> 00:34:15.210
might not otherwise
pay attention.

00:34:15.210 --> 00:34:19.250
So if you see a headline and
it’s Columbia spends $200

00:34:19.250 --> 00:34:22.010
million to the Treasury
in $21 million,

00:34:22.010 --> 00:34:26.010
largest ever EEOC religious
discrimination case.

00:34:26.010 --> 00:34:28.370
Actually, when you
see numbers like that,

00:34:28.370 --> 00:34:30.830
then you pay attention and
you look and then you’re able

00:34:30.830 --> 00:34:32.050
to learn a little bit more.

00:34:32.050 --> 00:34:34.155
So maybe you wouldn’t
normally learn.

00:34:34.155 --> 00:34:36.030
And are the people paying
attention, not just

00:34:36.030 --> 00:34:38.409
the public, but other
college presidents.

00:34:38.409 --> 00:34:40.070
Yeah you want to
get in early before

00:34:40.070 --> 00:34:42.130
the fines are too large.

00:34:42.130 --> 00:34:46.429
But I think in general,
a settlement on its own

00:34:46.429 --> 00:34:50.909
without a fine might not
be taken as seriously

00:34:50.909 --> 00:34:54.510
by the public or by
other universities

00:34:54.510 --> 00:34:56.929
as when there is a
fine, which I said,

00:34:56.929 --> 00:34:59.050
these are small dollar
figures compared

00:34:59.050 --> 00:35:00.550
to the amounts that
they are getting

00:35:00.550 --> 00:35:02.133
every year from the
federal government

00:35:02.133 --> 00:35:04.390
and from their donors.

00:35:04.390 --> 00:35:09.310
But I think it provides
a seriousness and a focus

00:35:09.310 --> 00:35:14.050
on these in ways that a
promises only wouldn’t.

00:35:14.050 --> 00:35:16.830
Do you think the biggest
schools are just too rich.

00:35:16.830 --> 00:35:19.710
The federal government
now under the first Trump

00:35:19.710 --> 00:35:23.150
administration, passed a
very modest endowment tax.

00:35:23.150 --> 00:35:24.910
Do you think generally
it would be better

00:35:24.910 --> 00:35:27.230
for America if the
biggest schools had

00:35:27.230 --> 00:35:28.910
smaller endowments.

00:35:28.910 --> 00:35:32.310
So I think it’s not
necessarily the size

00:35:32.310 --> 00:35:33.570
of the endowment.

00:35:33.570 --> 00:35:35.770
It’s the application of them.

00:35:35.770 --> 00:35:37.310
So are you putting
your endowment

00:35:37.310 --> 00:35:41.790
to some positive use, or is
this just generating capital

00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:42.610
so that later.

00:35:42.610 --> 00:35:44.750
You can have a
bigger building.

00:35:44.750 --> 00:35:46.690
There’s no problem
with being wealthy.

00:35:46.690 --> 00:35:49.310
There’s no problem with
universities being wealthy.

00:35:49.310 --> 00:35:52.010
But what are you
using your wealth for.

00:35:52.010 --> 00:35:54.830
I think you can judge on that.

00:35:54.830 --> 00:36:00.797
And, so if you’re saying I
need all this money for this

00:36:00.797 --> 00:36:02.380
research, where am
I going to find it.

00:36:02.380 --> 00:36:03.088
Where am I going.

00:36:03.088 --> 00:36:05.840
Well, I did find some of it.

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:08.800
And then if you were
using some of that money

00:36:08.800 --> 00:36:11.560
to fund research, that
would generate a patent that

00:36:11.560 --> 00:36:13.720
would be very
valuable, then that

00:36:13.720 --> 00:36:15.160
would be beneficial
for everybody

00:36:15.160 --> 00:36:16.880
because you have
put that money then

00:36:16.880 --> 00:36:18.920
to good and productive use.

00:36:18.920 --> 00:36:22.680
I want to ask how
ideas, ideology

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:25.880
and ideological diversity
enter into this.

00:36:25.880 --> 00:36:28.640
Because in one of the
publicized letters

00:36:28.640 --> 00:36:30.500
that the administration
sent to Harvard,

00:36:30.500 --> 00:36:32.560
there was a specific
focus on the idea

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:37.240
that Harvard should be looking
for intellectual diversity

00:36:37.240 --> 00:36:40.320
in hiring and considering
seriously why there are so few

00:36:40.320 --> 00:36:42.040
conservative and
Republican faculty

00:36:42.040 --> 00:36:44.220
and trying to do
something about that.

00:36:44.220 --> 00:36:47.500
And the letter took
this quite far right.

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:51.320
It specifically said that
Harvard should consider

00:36:51.320 --> 00:36:54.120
that each department
field or teaching

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:57.220
unit must be individually
viewpoint diverse.

00:36:57.220 --> 00:36:58.800
I’m quoting from
the letter here,

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:02.700
and that there should be a
audit that goes on a quote,

00:37:02.700 --> 00:37:06.360
Department by department,
field by field or teaching

00:37:06.360 --> 00:37:09.880
unit by teaching unit
basis as appropriate.

00:37:09.880 --> 00:37:11.760
End quote.

00:37:11.760 --> 00:37:16.200
And I should stress, this is
an area that as a conservative

00:37:16.200 --> 00:37:18.580
with a lot of experience
of higher education,

00:37:18.580 --> 00:37:22.720
take very seriously as a big
problem for elite academia

00:37:22.720 --> 00:37:25.080
that it isn’t
intellectually diverse.

00:37:25.080 --> 00:37:28.760
But it does seem like in this
ask can see the problem with

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:31.600
the federal government trying
to micromanage this because it

00:37:31.600 --> 00:37:34.880
just seems like you get
very quickly into an absurd

00:37:34.880 --> 00:37:37.460
situation where
someone in Washington,

00:37:37.460 --> 00:37:41.570
DC is scrutinizing Harvard’s
geology department.

00:37:41.570 --> 00:37:43.820
I don’t even know if Harvard
has a geology department,

00:37:43.820 --> 00:37:46.160
but you take my point to
see if it has enough Trump

00:37:46.160 --> 00:37:48.240
supporters.

00:37:48.240 --> 00:37:51.180
This is, I think, the
most difficult question,

00:37:51.180 --> 00:37:54.730
because the answer
is on one hand,

00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:57.850
obviously, I think
conservatives

00:37:57.850 --> 00:38:02.370
want universities to a prepare
their students and students

00:38:02.370 --> 00:38:05.010
are going to be in the
real world confronted

00:38:05.010 --> 00:38:07.090
with all sorts of
thoughts, and they

00:38:07.090 --> 00:38:08.550
should be prepared for that.

00:38:08.550 --> 00:38:12.690
So a good University
would have some level

00:38:12.690 --> 00:38:14.930
of intellectual diversity.

00:38:14.930 --> 00:38:20.810
And not only that, but to the
extent you have universities

00:38:20.810 --> 00:38:23.610
that are just hotbeds
of radicalism,

00:38:23.610 --> 00:38:25.217
that’s not good
for the student.

00:38:25.217 --> 00:38:26.550
That’s not good
for the culture,

00:38:26.550 --> 00:38:28.810
that’s not good
for the campus,

00:38:28.810 --> 00:38:31.390
that’s bad for the country.

00:38:31.390 --> 00:38:33.950
So that is all true.

00:38:33.950 --> 00:38:36.730
And I think the
administration believes

00:38:36.730 --> 00:38:40.290
that intellectual
diversity is a key factor

00:38:40.290 --> 00:38:44.770
to a good University that
we would send our kids to.

00:38:44.770 --> 00:38:49.330
But at the same time, I
think we all acknowledge that

00:38:49.330 --> 00:38:54.690
the federal government’s
role in policing that is

00:38:54.690 --> 00:38:59.370
necessarily limited in the
sense that we don’t want

00:38:59.370 --> 00:39:03.670
the next administration
to come in and say, well,

00:39:03.670 --> 00:39:07.450
actually, this is the mix
that I think is the best.

00:39:07.450 --> 00:39:10.930
So in meaning a Democratic
administration coming

00:39:10.930 --> 00:39:15.730
in and calling up University
of Kansas and saying,

00:39:15.730 --> 00:39:21.270
why haven’t you hired 17 more
leftists for EECS department.

00:39:21.270 --> 00:39:24.670
Exactly and it’s a ridiculous
thing to think through,

00:39:24.670 --> 00:39:27.410
because how many more
leftists can you possibly hire

00:39:27.410 --> 00:39:30.810
if you’re this
saturated already but.

00:39:30.810 --> 00:39:32.970
Well, but it is.

00:39:32.970 --> 00:39:36.390
I think that particular
example would not happen.

00:39:36.390 --> 00:39:41.050
But I think obviously, we saw
in the Obama administration

00:39:41.050 --> 00:39:43.690
and to some degree in the
Biden administration, right.

00:39:43.690 --> 00:39:46.490
Democratic administrations
were very comfortable

00:39:46.490 --> 00:39:49.370
using some of the same levers
the Trump administration is

00:39:49.370 --> 00:39:54.090
using to push college campuses
in particular directions

00:39:54.090 --> 00:39:55.530
on how to handle
sexual assault

00:39:55.530 --> 00:39:58.170
and how to handle transgender
issues, and so on.

00:39:58.170 --> 00:40:02.210
And I think one of the
critiques from a libertarian

00:40:02.210 --> 00:40:05.130
perspective of what the
Trump administration is doing

00:40:05.130 --> 00:40:11.050
is that you are of setting
up, taking that model

00:40:11.050 --> 00:40:12.310
and turbocharging it.

00:40:12.310 --> 00:40:15.650
And a Democratic
administration could say, hey,

00:40:15.650 --> 00:40:18.410
all of these Catholic
hospitals seem to be getting

00:40:18.410 --> 00:40:20.110
a lot of public
health care funding,

00:40:20.110 --> 00:40:23.990
and yet they won’t perform
gender reassignment surgeries.

00:40:23.990 --> 00:40:29.450
Let’s do something about
that escalatory spiral once

00:40:29.450 --> 00:40:34.570
the federal government is
providing private institutions

00:40:34.570 --> 00:40:36.390
that get public money
with marching orders.

00:40:36.390 --> 00:40:38.790
I think that’s a
reasonable concern.

00:40:38.790 --> 00:40:43.830
So civil rights, I think,
is easy meritocracy is good.

00:40:43.830 --> 00:40:48.620
And the hope actually is that
if you are actually treating

00:40:48.620 --> 00:40:53.660
people on the basis of their
merit and whether that’s test

00:40:53.660 --> 00:40:56.300
scores or whether that’s
personal successes

00:40:56.300 --> 00:40:59.940
or whatever, you do tend
to handle the intellectual

00:40:59.940 --> 00:41:05.020
diversity piece by accident,
because it’s not going to be

00:41:05.020 --> 00:41:09.180
the case that every excellent
person thinks the same thing.

00:41:09.180 --> 00:41:11.700
So there’s that.

00:41:11.700 --> 00:41:16.700
But then also, I think that’s
why it’s important that this

00:41:16.700 --> 00:41:20.500
process come under way, where
there’s a conversation with

00:41:20.500 --> 00:41:23.780
universities and with
donors and with the Trump

00:41:23.780 --> 00:41:26.460
administration altogether,
about what it actually means

00:41:26.460 --> 00:41:29.188
to be a great University
and to have buy in.

00:41:29.188 --> 00:41:30.980
Because I actually
think one of the reasons

00:41:30.980 --> 00:41:33.740
why some of these
universities have made changes

00:41:33.740 --> 00:41:37.180
without provocation from
the Trump administration,

00:41:37.180 --> 00:41:40.140
or in the case of
Columbia, even though there

00:41:40.140 --> 00:41:42.360
was provocation and even
though it was a deal,

00:41:42.360 --> 00:41:44.367
is because they wanted
to they wanted to

00:41:44.367 --> 00:41:46.200
and they thought that
this was a good thing,

00:41:46.200 --> 00:41:48.460
and they were tired
of being held hostage

00:41:48.460 --> 00:41:49.560
by their left wing.

00:41:49.560 --> 00:41:51.920
And actually, they want
intellectual diversity.

00:41:51.920 --> 00:41:55.260
They don’t want another person
who’s just going to have

00:41:55.260 --> 00:41:57.820
the same we got another
climate change person,

00:41:57.820 --> 00:42:00.120
we’ve got another
gender studies person.

00:42:00.120 --> 00:42:01.800
I think they want it.

00:42:01.800 --> 00:42:06.020
And so giving the universities
the permission to do this

00:42:06.020 --> 00:42:09.380
sometimes requires a strong
statement from the government

00:42:09.380 --> 00:42:11.600
that’s almost
like a scapegoat.

00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:15.160
But yeah, I think
that’s right.

00:42:15.160 --> 00:42:18.500
Based just based on my own
experience living in a college

00:42:18.500 --> 00:42:21.680
town and speaking to people
who work in higher education,

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:23.907
that there is
some degree first,

00:42:23.907 --> 00:42:25.740
to which the Trump
administration is pushing

00:42:25.740 --> 00:42:29.100
on an open door, and also
some degree to which leaders

00:42:29.100 --> 00:42:32.060
of universities are
happy to say oh,

00:42:32.060 --> 00:42:35.420
we didn’t want to do this, but
the Trump administration made

00:42:35.420 --> 00:42:36.640
us do it right.

00:42:36.640 --> 00:42:39.180
But in fact, it’s something
that they themselves want

00:42:39.180 --> 00:42:40.460
to do.

00:42:40.460 --> 00:42:42.580
At the same time,
though, I do think

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:45.510
that there is some
tension between saying,

00:42:45.510 --> 00:42:48.850
we want schools to hire
just based on merit,

00:42:48.850 --> 00:42:51.470
and we want schools to have
a lot more intellectual

00:42:51.470 --> 00:42:54.270
diversity, because the
reality is and this

00:42:54.270 --> 00:42:56.510
is where I think the
traditional left wing

00:42:56.510 --> 00:42:58.230
argument around
affirmative action

00:42:58.230 --> 00:42:59.730
always made a certain sense.

00:42:59.730 --> 00:43:02.770
You have to create
pipelines, right.

00:43:02.770 --> 00:43:05.830
I think it was reasonable in
the 1960s to say there just

00:43:05.830 --> 00:43:07.550
aren’t good pipelines
for getting a lot

00:43:07.550 --> 00:43:10.290
of African-American kids
into elite colleges.

00:43:10.290 --> 00:43:12.750
I think it’s reasonable for
conservatives today to say

00:43:12.750 --> 00:43:15.630
there aren’t good pipelines
for getting people who aren’t

00:43:15.630 --> 00:43:18.670
left wing into certain
academic departments.

00:43:18.670 --> 00:43:23.590
But I just think you aren’t
going to get there by saying

00:43:23.590 --> 00:43:24.610
merit alone.

00:43:24.610 --> 00:43:25.170
You are.

00:43:25.170 --> 00:43:26.650
You would have to say no.

00:43:26.650 --> 00:43:31.350
Universities have to do
proactive things that

00:43:31.350 --> 00:43:34.010
are Yeah, going to be
in tension a little bit.

00:43:34.010 --> 00:43:38.870
The affirmative action for the
conservative is it’s an actual

00:43:38.870 --> 00:43:39.370
reality.

00:43:39.370 --> 00:43:43.630
When I was in Harvard there,
we had maybe 1 and 1/2

00:43:43.630 --> 00:43:48.390
conservative professors and
I think the University surely

00:43:48.390 --> 00:43:53.710
Adrian Vermeule counts
for at least like 3.7.

00:43:53.710 --> 00:43:55.550
That is true.

00:43:55.550 --> 00:43:59.050
But the pipelines
thing, I think,

00:43:59.050 --> 00:44:01.850
is different than actual
affirmative action.

00:44:01.850 --> 00:44:04.410
And looking at
your criteria too.

00:44:04.410 --> 00:44:08.110
So if what you are
prioritizing is how many times

00:44:08.110 --> 00:44:11.650
you’ve been published in
some leftist magazine, then,

00:44:11.650 --> 00:44:15.310
of course, a conservative is
not going to compete there.

00:44:15.310 --> 00:44:18.550
But I think other universities
have found successes

00:44:18.550 --> 00:44:20.612
in having some
adjunct programs.

00:44:20.612 --> 00:44:21.570
You’re not a professor.

00:44:21.570 --> 00:44:23.862
You’re not going to be able
to compete on those levels.

00:44:23.862 --> 00:44:27.150
But we’re going to bring you
in and you can teach a January

00:44:27.150 --> 00:44:31.210
course, or you can have a
clinic or something like that.

00:44:31.210 --> 00:44:37.150
So I think this problem starts
incrementally solving itself

00:44:37.150 --> 00:44:41.520
in a way that doesn’t
ultimately require affirmative

00:44:41.520 --> 00:44:44.160
action, and then groups
like the Federalist Society.

00:44:44.160 --> 00:44:46.480
They try and
identify people who

00:44:46.480 --> 00:44:49.360
they think would
be good professors

00:44:49.360 --> 00:44:53.240
and try and teach
them how to do that.

00:44:53.240 --> 00:44:56.520
No, no, I don’t think there’s
any problem with the pipeline

00:44:56.520 --> 00:44:59.400
in law schools, but I think
the Federalist Society is

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:01.180
a fairly distinctive case.

00:45:01.180 --> 00:45:06.680
And let me throw out another
seeming tension here,

00:45:06.680 --> 00:45:09.740
which is around issues
about anti-Semitism.

00:45:09.740 --> 00:45:12.800
So, clearly there
are certain things

00:45:12.800 --> 00:45:15.920
that universities have
tolerated or allowed

00:45:15.920 --> 00:45:18.560
in protests in
the last few years

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:21.640
that are just overt
harassment and intimidation

00:45:21.640 --> 00:45:22.980
of Jewish students.

00:45:22.980 --> 00:45:24.940
And I think there it’s
very straightforward.

00:45:24.940 --> 00:45:27.680
What the administration
is asking for.

00:45:27.680 --> 00:45:32.280
But then there’s a larger,
very blurry zone of critiques

00:45:32.280 --> 00:45:34.180
of the policies of
the state of Israel.

00:45:34.180 --> 00:45:35.620
Critiques of Zionism.

00:45:35.620 --> 00:45:41.800
Where the administration
has seemed

00:45:41.800 --> 00:45:45.540
to ask in some cases
for something that,

00:45:45.540 --> 00:45:48.880
again, looks more
like micromanaging

00:45:48.880 --> 00:45:51.340
of particular departments.

00:45:51.340 --> 00:45:54.960
Saying, well, we’re not
going to have radical critics

00:45:54.960 --> 00:45:56.120
of Israel here and there.

00:45:56.120 --> 00:45:56.620
And so on.

00:45:56.620 --> 00:46:00.920
And that, again, seems
like a kind of thumb

00:46:00.920 --> 00:46:03.020
on the scale in
intellectual debates.

00:46:03.020 --> 00:46:07.920
So when you say the Trump
administration has asked

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:10.760
for them, I acknowledge that
there are some letters that

00:46:10.760 --> 00:46:15.880
were sent by the anti-Semitism
task force in some way

00:46:15.880 --> 00:46:20.200
that either incorporated
the IHRA definition

00:46:20.200 --> 00:46:24.113
or otherwise were perceived
to have been speech codes.

00:46:24.113 --> 00:46:24.780
These are right.

00:46:24.780 --> 00:46:27.080
These are strong
definitions of anti-Semitism

00:46:27.080 --> 00:46:31.080
that at least some people on
the left would say rule out

00:46:31.080 --> 00:46:33.140
what should be legitimate
critiques of right.

00:46:33.140 --> 00:46:35.880
But when you look at
what President Trump

00:46:35.880 --> 00:46:38.980
and at the Sr. level, what
has actually happened.

00:46:38.980 --> 00:46:39.980
It’s not that.

00:46:39.980 --> 00:46:41.613
So the Columbia
deal, and I think

00:46:41.613 --> 00:46:43.280
everyone would
acknowledge that Columbia

00:46:43.280 --> 00:46:46.600
had a major
anti-Semitism problem,

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:51.080
but the Columbia
deal in no way

00:46:51.080 --> 00:46:53.640
creates any speech
code, whether it be

00:46:53.640 --> 00:46:55.480
on Israel or anything else.

00:46:55.480 --> 00:46:56.220
It does not.

00:46:56.220 --> 00:47:01.240
It specifically says that this
is not intended to create any

00:47:01.240 --> 00:47:05.120
First Amendment conflict
or otherwise govern speech

00:47:05.120 --> 00:47:06.660
on Columbia’s campus.

00:47:06.660 --> 00:47:10.320
So there’s a concern and
I think there are people

00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:14.480
in the administration who
probably are more in favor

00:47:14.480 --> 00:47:17.040
of speech constraints and then
people who are less in favor

00:47:17.040 --> 00:47:18.208
of speech constraints.

00:47:18.208 --> 00:47:20.500
And that’s just the way the
Trump administration works,

00:47:20.500 --> 00:47:22.860
where people have different
views of where that line is.

00:47:22.860 --> 00:47:24.985
And I think it’s a difficult
conversation of what’s

00:47:24.985 --> 00:47:30.760
the line between harassment
and being unable to actually

00:47:30.760 --> 00:47:37.465
function on campus, right
versus fair criticism that

00:47:37.465 --> 00:47:39.590
people, even if they don’t
like it, should hear it.

00:47:39.590 --> 00:47:41.350
That’s not a definable line.

00:47:41.350 --> 00:47:43.010
That is a difficult line.

00:47:43.010 --> 00:47:44.590
And I think in
sussing that out,

00:47:44.590 --> 00:47:47.530
at the end of the day, where
the Trump administration

00:47:47.530 --> 00:47:51.990
landed is on the more free
speech side of things,

00:47:51.990 --> 00:47:56.490
which is evident in the final
terms of the Columbia deal.

00:47:56.490 --> 00:48:01.410
O.K, let’s talk for a
minute about the legality

00:48:01.410 --> 00:48:03.910
of the approach the Trump
administration has taken.

00:48:03.910 --> 00:48:08.610
Because I think you have
conceded to some degree

00:48:08.610 --> 00:48:11.370
that, in all of these
zones, there are

00:48:11.370 --> 00:48:14.170
gray areas and blurry lines.

00:48:14.170 --> 00:48:19.850
However, the administration
has also moved preemptively

00:48:19.850 --> 00:48:24.670
to cut funding to say, it is
and correct me if I’m wrong,

00:48:24.670 --> 00:48:27.610
but my understanding is what
has happened repeatedly is

00:48:27.610 --> 00:48:30.010
critiques have been lodged,
investigations have been

00:48:30.010 --> 00:48:33.610
opened, and then funding
has been cut before

00:48:33.610 --> 00:48:35.530
the investigation is complete.

00:48:35.530 --> 00:48:37.970
And this is where the
Trump administration

00:48:37.970 --> 00:48:42.090
has been rebuked in
court in, most recently

00:48:42.090 --> 00:48:47.090
in a case involving Harvard
itself for this right that you

00:48:47.090 --> 00:48:49.610
are essentially
assuming the violation

00:48:49.610 --> 00:48:53.610
before the negotiation
is actually finished.

00:48:53.610 --> 00:48:56.770
Is that a fair critique
So that is certainly

00:48:56.770 --> 00:48:58.190
what Harvard says.

00:48:58.190 --> 00:49:01.540
Yes, and I think.

00:49:04.410 --> 00:49:05.910
It’s different
than that though.

00:49:05.910 --> 00:49:09.570
So Yes, Title Vi, which
says you can’t discriminate

00:49:09.570 --> 00:49:12.910
on the basis of race,
is a bar on funding.

00:49:12.910 --> 00:49:15.750
So if you are found
to violate Title Vi,

00:49:15.750 --> 00:49:18.650
that’s not grants
that are at issue.

00:49:18.650 --> 00:49:20.510
That’s your student loans.

00:49:20.510 --> 00:49:21.910
That’s Pell grants.

00:49:21.910 --> 00:49:23.990
I mean, that’s a big deal.

00:49:23.990 --> 00:49:27.675
If you are found, if you
are violated right now, what

00:49:27.675 --> 00:49:29.050
the Trump
administration has done

00:49:29.050 --> 00:49:32.300
is not find a
Title Vi violation

00:49:32.300 --> 00:49:33.960
prior to the process.

00:49:33.960 --> 00:49:37.240
I mean, the Title Vi
violation was found.

00:49:37.240 --> 00:49:39.960
HHS did find them in
violation of Title Vi,

00:49:39.960 --> 00:49:41.380
and referred that
case over to DOJ

00:49:41.380 --> 00:49:46.500
to litigate and informed
the accreditor for Harvard.

00:49:46.500 --> 00:49:51.787
But this is an entity that
doesn’t have share the values,

00:49:51.787 --> 00:49:53.120
basically of the
administration.

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:55.700
And there are various statutes
and various regulations

00:49:55.700 --> 00:49:59.300
that give the administration
that discretion over how

00:49:59.300 --> 00:50:01.420
it can spend its own money.

00:50:01.420 --> 00:50:08.600
And so the lawsuit basically
was an argument that oh, well,

00:50:08.600 --> 00:50:11.700
they’re just saying that, but
what they’re actually doing is

00:50:11.700 --> 00:50:13.820
short circuiting the
Title Vi process.

00:50:13.820 --> 00:50:14.740
Well, right.

00:50:14.740 --> 00:50:17.360
And it does I mean, it
does seem, in fairness,

00:50:17.360 --> 00:50:19.280
right from our
entire conversation,

00:50:19.280 --> 00:50:23.660
that the goal of the Trump
administration’s strategy is

00:50:23.660 --> 00:50:26.700
not to micromanage
how Harvard,

00:50:26.700 --> 00:50:29.100
how Harvard does cancer
research or whatever it is

00:50:29.100 --> 00:50:32.900
to change University policy
on hiring and discrimination

00:50:32.900 --> 00:50:33.920
and anti-Semitism.

00:50:33.920 --> 00:50:36.720
So doesn’t it seem
like that’s true,

00:50:36.720 --> 00:50:40.220
that you are picking these
grants as a lever to affect

00:50:40.220 --> 00:50:41.860
something unrelated to them.

00:50:41.860 --> 00:50:44.600
Having Harvard change its
policies would be great,

00:50:44.600 --> 00:50:47.107
but at the same time, if
they don’t, that’s fine.

00:50:47.107 --> 00:50:48.440
We’re just not
going to fund it.

00:50:48.440 --> 00:50:52.640
And so it’s not like
it’s taking over Harvard.

00:50:52.640 --> 00:50:54.800
They sued us.

00:50:54.800 --> 00:50:55.720
We didn’t sue them.

00:50:55.720 --> 00:50:58.020
It’s not a forced change.

00:50:58.020 --> 00:51:01.100
It is actually just that
there’s a portion not even

00:51:01.100 --> 00:51:01.600
all.

00:51:01.600 --> 00:51:04.620
There is a portion of
Harvard’s grants that we just

00:51:04.620 --> 00:51:07.120
decide should go
to somewhere else.

00:51:07.120 --> 00:51:10.120
Maybe another University,
maybe Brown, maybe Princeton,

00:51:10.120 --> 00:51:11.660
maybe Yale.

00:51:11.660 --> 00:51:15.380
I’m just going to express
some skepticism that the Trump

00:51:15.380 --> 00:51:18.740
administration has
sat down and said,

00:51:18.740 --> 00:51:22.300
we really think that the
University of Kansas Cancer

00:51:22.300 --> 00:51:25.660
research program is just
way better than Harvard’s.

00:51:25.660 --> 00:51:28.410
And we’re just going
to cut that funding.

00:51:28.410 --> 00:51:31.070
It seems like the
administration

00:51:31.070 --> 00:51:37.510
is going after going after
the areas where Harvard is,

00:51:37.510 --> 00:51:40.970
by general agreement, most
effective and successful,

00:51:40.970 --> 00:51:43.350
because that seems
like a useful lever

00:51:43.350 --> 00:51:46.210
to change other areas of
administration policy.

00:51:46.210 --> 00:51:49.970
But at the end that isn’t
that that’s a naive reading,

00:51:49.970 --> 00:51:51.290
a straight A simple reading.

00:51:51.290 --> 00:51:55.030
It’s not a full comparison
of all universities across

00:51:55.030 --> 00:51:56.190
the nation.

00:51:56.190 --> 00:52:02.230
But at the end of the day,
Harvard reacted to a letter

00:52:02.230 --> 00:52:08.430
that asked for a few simple
changes with a lawsuit that

00:52:08.430 --> 00:52:13.150
basically said, instead of
us showing any amount of good

00:52:13.150 --> 00:52:16.590
faith effort to commit
ourselves to the policies that

00:52:16.590 --> 00:52:18.430
are important to
the United States,

00:52:18.430 --> 00:52:23.630
we’re going to instead say,
we refuse to even answer you.

00:52:23.630 --> 00:52:25.770
These are billions
of federal dollars.

00:52:25.770 --> 00:52:30.030
And I think that
the funder of that

00:52:30.030 --> 00:52:32.510
can ask for a
basic relationship.

00:52:32.510 --> 00:52:33.010
All right.

00:52:33.010 --> 00:52:36.130
Well, let’s end by
looking at the future.

00:52:36.130 --> 00:52:39.630
Imagine it is 2030.

00:52:39.630 --> 00:52:43.270
And I guess we well, we
can imagine it’s either

00:52:43.270 --> 00:52:45.850
a Democratic or a
Republican administration.

00:52:45.850 --> 00:52:51.570
Give me a definition of
success in higher Ed policy.

00:52:51.570 --> 00:52:55.230
In 5 in five years and
seven years or eight years,

00:52:55.230 --> 00:52:57.110
what does the
landscape look like

00:52:57.110 --> 00:53:01.190
if your negotiations with
and pressure on universities

00:53:01.190 --> 00:53:03.070
are successful.

00:53:03.070 --> 00:53:08.110
So I think universities will
return to a merit mission

00:53:08.110 --> 00:53:11.970
and that’ll be in admissions,
that’ll be in hiring,

00:53:11.970 --> 00:53:14.150
that’ll be in research.

00:53:14.150 --> 00:53:17.150
And so that’ll be with its
relationship to the federal

00:53:17.150 --> 00:53:19.870
government, that the federal
government will be funding

00:53:19.870 --> 00:53:23.610
institutions that can be
perceived as excellent.

00:53:23.610 --> 00:53:25.170
And maybe they’re not today.

00:53:25.170 --> 00:53:27.310
Excellent maybe they are
these institutions that

00:53:27.310 --> 00:53:31.750
are trying to be excellent,
but that the mission

00:53:31.750 --> 00:53:34.470
of universities will
not be diversity.

00:53:34.470 --> 00:53:38.350
The mission of universities
won’t be equity,

00:53:38.350 --> 00:53:41.170
but they will be excellence.

00:53:41.170 --> 00:53:45.630
And that will be rewarded with
a tighter, closer and better

00:53:45.630 --> 00:53:47.390
federal relationship.

00:53:47.390 --> 00:53:49.690
And so that’s with regard
to the federal government,

00:53:49.690 --> 00:53:51.170
I think policies
larger than that,

00:53:51.170 --> 00:53:53.710
policies like what’s its
effect in the world and how

00:53:53.710 --> 00:53:55.630
does it change our culture.

00:53:55.630 --> 00:53:57.990
And my hope is
that the people who

00:53:57.990 --> 00:54:00.830
are graduating from
our universities

00:54:00.830 --> 00:54:06.390
carry values that will
uplift Western civilization

00:54:06.390 --> 00:54:07.830
and our country.

00:54:07.830 --> 00:54:10.630
And so that installation
of values is obviously not

00:54:10.630 --> 00:54:14.590
something that the federal
government can necessarily

00:54:14.590 --> 00:54:17.910
micromanage, but it’s
something that the University

00:54:17.910 --> 00:54:22.800
itself can recommit itself
to in determining how can we

00:54:22.800 --> 00:54:27.440
prepare our student body to
be true leaders and to advance

00:54:27.440 --> 00:54:31.240
our country in ways that
will be better for everybody.

00:54:31.240 --> 00:54:35.600
And to the extent that
universities don’t act

00:54:35.600 --> 00:54:39.220
collaboratively
with this change.

00:54:39.220 --> 00:54:43.440
Do you imagine a landscape
where there really is a kind

00:54:43.440 --> 00:54:47.380
of shift in prestige and
where students go, let’s say,

00:54:47.380 --> 00:54:50.100
from the Northeast to
the South or Southwest.

00:54:50.100 --> 00:54:54.960
Would you imagine a kind of
shaken up US News and World

00:54:54.960 --> 00:54:58.800
Report rankings or something
as a possible outcome of all

00:54:58.800 --> 00:54:59.760
of this.

00:54:59.760 --> 00:55:06.160
So I do think that as
universities decide that they

00:55:06.160 --> 00:55:10.160
don’t want a merit seeking
mission that’s not attractive

00:55:10.160 --> 00:55:12.740
for parents, that’s not
attractive for students,

00:55:12.740 --> 00:55:14.980
and it’s not attractive
for the federal government.

00:55:14.980 --> 00:55:18.000
It’s also not
attractive for donors.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.400
And they’ll and they’ll have
to be more out loud about

00:55:20.400 --> 00:55:20.900
that.

00:55:20.900 --> 00:55:21.400
So that.

00:55:21.400 --> 00:55:24.360
So I think that’s the goal is
you can choose who you want

00:55:24.360 --> 00:55:24.860
to be.

00:55:24.860 --> 00:55:26.500
You want to make no changes.

00:55:26.500 --> 00:55:28.300
You want to commit
yourself to victimhood.

00:55:28.300 --> 00:55:31.360
You want to oppose
the idea of merit.

00:55:31.360 --> 00:55:35.280
Say it out loud so that
students, parents, donors

00:55:35.280 --> 00:55:38.920
and the government can know
and that each can dedicate

00:55:38.920 --> 00:55:42.000
their resources to those
universities that are

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:45.000
making our country better.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:51.040
Last question then, from my
perspective can probably sense

00:55:51.040 --> 00:55:53.520
this from some of the
questions I’ve asked.

00:55:53.520 --> 00:55:58.160
The core weakness to me
of University culture

00:55:58.160 --> 00:56:01.840
is a kind of stifling
intellectual conformism.

00:56:01.840 --> 00:56:05.000
But that also seems to me
just from watching the Trump

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:07.960
administration in its
battles with universities,

00:56:07.960 --> 00:56:10.080
the hardest for
government policy

00:56:10.080 --> 00:56:13.800
to address without either
falling afoul of the First

00:56:13.800 --> 00:56:17.400
Amendment or getting into
impossible micromanaging.

00:56:17.400 --> 00:56:22.050
And it seems to me that a
really shrewd federal strategy

00:56:22.050 --> 00:56:26.290
could take you from a world
where 2 percent of the Harvard

00:56:26.290 --> 00:56:29.450
faculty are conservatives to
a world where 4 percent are

00:56:29.450 --> 00:56:30.550
conservative, right.

00:56:30.550 --> 00:56:35.650
And could get you some
slightly more meaningful

00:56:35.650 --> 00:56:37.150
intellectual diversity.

00:56:37.150 --> 00:56:39.970
But to get beyond
that need as you just

00:56:39.970 --> 00:56:45.810
suggested, some kind of
larger cultural shift.

00:56:45.810 --> 00:56:47.690
Universities did
not become liberal

00:56:47.690 --> 00:56:50.430
because the federal government
told them to become liberal.

00:56:50.430 --> 00:56:53.610
They became liberal
because academic culture

00:56:53.610 --> 00:56:57.210
moved substantially to the
left in a kind of organic way.

00:56:57.210 --> 00:56:59.810
And the same with
student culture.

00:56:59.810 --> 00:57:03.410
Can you imagine a
shift in the culture

00:57:03.410 --> 00:57:08.210
that would create greater
intellectual diversity

00:57:08.210 --> 00:57:10.970
on college campuses.

00:57:10.970 --> 00:57:15.370
So if we’re talking about
federal and non-federal

00:57:15.370 --> 00:57:17.610
levers, I think a
couple of things.

00:57:17.610 --> 00:57:19.730
So one, I think
the same change

00:57:19.730 --> 00:57:21.450
that the Federalist
Society has

00:57:21.450 --> 00:57:25.350
brought for law schools
could be focused on.

00:57:25.350 --> 00:57:29.130
And, I want to take a moment
for Charlie Kirk and Turning

00:57:29.130 --> 00:57:39.210
Point, because the quiet loser
of the Republican Party when I

00:57:39.210 --> 00:57:41.750
was in college
doesn’t exist now.

00:57:41.750 --> 00:57:46.130
I think people are braver now,
and they have community now.

00:57:46.130 --> 00:57:51.330
And so you can see a turning
point type organization.

00:57:51.330 --> 00:57:54.750
Try and figure out then
how to make professors,

00:57:54.750 --> 00:57:59.030
how to bring that energy
into leadership levels.

00:57:59.030 --> 00:58:02.490
So think you could do some
conservative organizing

00:58:02.490 --> 00:58:05.410
around already
successful groups.

00:58:05.410 --> 00:58:07.510
And then I think
just competition.

00:58:07.510 --> 00:58:11.250
So President Trump said, he
wanted to take Harvard’s money

00:58:11.250 --> 00:58:13.203
and give it to trade schools.

00:58:13.203 --> 00:58:15.370
And obviously, you’re not
going to take NIH research

00:58:15.370 --> 00:58:18.340
money and give it to the
local cosmetology school.

00:58:18.340 --> 00:58:21.780
But I think the
general idea there is

00:58:21.780 --> 00:58:26.220
can have a robust
intellectual environment

00:58:26.220 --> 00:58:27.440
in a lot of different places.

00:58:27.440 --> 00:58:30.920
And it doesn’t have to be the
traditional University model.

00:58:30.920 --> 00:58:33.740
So if you just want to learn
about AI or if you want to do

00:58:33.740 --> 00:58:36.860
something different and it’s
maybe not your traditional

00:58:36.860 --> 00:58:40.900
liberal arts, but you
could having more options

00:58:40.900 --> 00:58:43.200
and universities wanting to
still attract those people.

00:58:43.200 --> 00:58:45.240
That type of
competition, I think,

00:58:45.240 --> 00:58:49.060
will increase the amount
of intellectual diversity

00:58:49.060 --> 00:58:51.420
that universities
have to offer.

00:58:51.420 --> 00:58:53.960
So continuing to find ways
to provide competition,

00:58:53.960 --> 00:58:56.080
I think is also important.

00:58:56.080 --> 00:58:56.900
All right.

00:58:56.900 --> 00:58:59.080
May Mailman, Thank you
so much for joining me.

00:58:59.080 --> 00:59:00.890
Thank you.

